segments.text: It was a cozy bunch of buildings approximately half block long in each direction.
The buildings were right up to the sidewalk.
The sidewalk was roughly 10 feet wide concrete.
As you leave the campus, on the right was
University Pharmacy or something like that.
You go by that and then there was, down the way you got to Holick's, the cleaners and booters across the street.
Further down was the KC and
They were both headquartered over in San Antonio.
Well, they had the Army business over there.
They had a lot of business there.
All right.
Was the campus theater?
It was a block west toward, right.
Were they...
There's a Dixie Chicken and some more stuff in there that didn't exist.
All right, Lupo wasn't there yet, was he?
Yeah, Lou came in.
He was more or less on the west side of the street.
On that corner?
Yeah, he came in there a number of times before that.
Okay, you were on an all-male campus.
How often were there young ladies coming to A&M for social events or anything else?
Well, in the fall, if there was a home football game, then there was a ball,
for the dance on the Friday night, and it was sponsored by Santa's Club, which one was it?
And then after the ball game, I was at the dance.
I'll take the fact that lots of times we just went to the dance after the game.
And that was held where?
At Vince Pizza Hall.
They always did a marvelous job of setting it up.
They had a big
But that would be after football games, beginning right in the middle of February.
It would be a constant
uh social weekend every week they uh start out with the red blood ball up at denton this evening because a lot of the a m activities are put into the tsc but then there'd be the cotton ball and
Then with each of those, there'd be a Friday night ball.
So if you say a ball, then you're talking about a Saturday night big time dance.
And they would run until they ran out of athletes.
But each regiment had its ball.
And twice I was cheering on the Coastal Artillery Ball.
Then there was a senior dance and a ring dance.
Well, no.
Usually what happened about in the end of February, there would be the sophomore ball.
It might hook up to one side or the other of the cotton ball.
Anyway, there was the sophomore ball, and then you run through the various organizations
You could have them in there as a junior prom for the leading Friday night dance.
And then the final ball of all was the senior ring dance.
And that's when they had the big ring.
The prospective couple put the kiss in the middle of the ring.
And that's there.
Engagement.
Engagement.
I was chairman of the Post-Sanctuary Ball twice and the Junior Comm once and the Senior Engagements.
I found out that that was the spring of 43 and it was real nice to be in those positions because I got to go to either Fort Worth or Houston and audition in those orchestras.
Now, were there some big name orchestras that came during those years?
We suffered a little bit in comparison with the University of Texas.
But we had Rand Wild and we had a number of others that were big.
They weren't Ben Miller, but they were next number.
Okay, all right.
Okay, let's go back now and lead me toward your getting called to active duty.
Well, in December of 42, they gave us, said you're now in the Invested Reserve Corps, and you're here to order away.
That was...
later part of my first semester here as a sophomore.
I was, I was just as adaptable to staying there and getting all the education I could because wherever I ended up, I'd be better off.
We went through then
the year 42 and lots of lots of all kinds of physical conditioning a little more intense on the military science and we kept going with a class of 43
they left in January of 43.
We had gone through the summer of 42, both they, class 43, which was us, and myself, every other 45.
We had all gone to school during the summer of 42, and then to spring of 43.
So you were
chronologically moving at a faster rate toward degree than you would have in peacetime?
Right there I'll tell you another one of those stories you're going to hear about.
Mitchell, I mean Hart Hall and Vassell Hall cross military walks on each other.
There was one fellow in heart that was just a particularly obnoxious character.
And you might, you wonder a little bit on how the core discipline itself, but this guy was just really a first-class bad-ass.
So, it got to be the middle of the summer, the temperature was just higher in Maryland,
No air conditioning, no going, no relief coming.
And this guy, he'd come in in the middle of the night and make a lot of racket.
Nobody would live with him if he was by himself.
And he didn't even put a mattress cover on his mattress.
He'd come in and make a lot of racket from slamming around.
And then he'd fall on the cot and go to sleep.
Well, this guy lived there a little bit older.
So they have contrived to go over there and pick up some fine wire and wire it up on the screen and then line that wire clear across over to Brazil.
And they went back then and
So they waited until the time was right.
That's when they knew he was in and the door was shut while they pulled the line tight to the skyrocket on there.
the eyes on the sky rocket, set it off, and that sky rocket whooshed, you know, and it went through that screen like it wasn't anything there.

Got inside and the rockets going around and around, all kind of fire techniques and everything, you know, the guy screaming bloody murder, let him out of there, you know, and finally go boom, you know.
Now you didn't have any part in that, you just, you were just aware of it.
I just heard about that.
Oh, I tell you that.
He got his couple come up.
As we're approaching 1942 and 43, did the coursework, academic coursework that y'all were assigned, did that change because of the war?
No.
No, of course, I've taken mechanical engineering.
So you were still in engineering, and you took the normal courses that an engineering student would have taken.
Yeah, and things progressed along.
I think we covered the social thing until the spring of 43.
Every weekend, there was two balls.
But we went into the last semester, of course,
We had no idea the school didn't need it.
Well, as you got close to the end of the semester, this would be like, well, in March of 43, the Army sent for all of us in the class of 44 and all of us in the class of 45 to go
and be actually inducted into the Army.
Up until then, we'd been in a reserve corps.
We were inducted into the Army.
Now, how and where was that done?
Well, they put us up in different places.
There was Camp Colt, Louisiana, Camp Beauregard, Fort Walters.
In my case, I went to Fort St. Houston, San Antonio.
In each case, why, we went to these, they had a crew train, crew train cars and all this.
When did you leave the campus for that?
Oh, one day in the middle of the week.
Did you finish, you didn't finish the semester in spring?
Oh yeah, we went back.
Oh, oh, oh, you went for that and then went back, okay.
Well, basically all we did, we went over there and got GI uniform and all the issues.
And took an oath?
Yeah.
And when were you given an Army serial number?
At that time.
At that time, okay.
Did they tell you when you would be called to active duty?
We didn't have any idea.
We just knew it was sooner than it had been.
Okay.
About that time,
President Gilchrist went into some long gone out exhausting efforts with the Army to give us six more weeks and it gave us four degrees.
And the President really tried.
I don't know if it was the first one.
But the Army never did do that.
So on May the 6th
How did you learn you'd been called?
Did they call all your group together and read it out or did you get a letter in the mail?
I got an order sooner or later.
I don't, you know, we were all there in a unit, and everybody in the unit was gone, so we just load up and go.
Our units basically stayed together until we got over to Fort Sam Houston.
Right, and did you go directly from College Station to Fort Sam?
Yeah, they had a trip coming for us.
And so you didn't go home and leave any civilian things?
You went straight.
Okay.
Now, by that time, you...
There was a time now between when we had gone after the uniforms and the others, and we knew then we were into it.
All right.
By this time, you had met a special young lady.
Let's digress back off.
Oh, that's way back to the NLTCU game in 1941.
All right.
How did that come about?
Well...
This was a court trip?
It was a Corps trip to Fort Worth in 1941.
I was there and we marched in the parade and went to the game and we won in Canada.
And when I got back home, I had not planned to do anything.
But there was an A&M Corps dance after
Texas Hotel.
And these freshman friends of mine, I was a sophomore, these freshman friends of mine who, one of them had lived in Fort Worth before.
There were three of them and they decided they wanted to go to, they had dates from TSCW to go to the dance.
And they said, come on, go.
I said, oh, I'm out of my girlfriends.
All my high school girlfriends are gone.
They said, oh, come on.
So I found a girl that I knew.
Never had a date with her before or since.
But anyway, she accepted the date.
So those guys came by, and just fairly dark.
Now she was another guy's date?
And I slammed that door and said, wait a minute, I've got to put myself together.
Well, fortunately, she and I, although I had a date with this other girl and she had a date with another guy, she and I really had a good time.
And she was from where?
Little Rock.
Little Rock.
She was going to school at Denton.
Oh, she was at TSCW, okay.
And then after that, how did you all communicate with each other?
Well, the U.S. Mail had a lot to do with it.
I could get a letter in the college station post office at 10 p.m. And she would have it at 9 a.m. Because of the railroad.
Yeah.
And she could tell you how she passed chemistry because she would send me the formulas.
And I would balance the equations and send them back to her.
And I could do all that in the time frame.
She made a good grading counselor.
And how often did you call her on the telephone?
Oh, gee.
The phone was expensive and hard to get.
I don't even think once a month.
Do you remember the first time she came to College Station?
Oh, yeah.
How long after that first dance was that?
Well, I think there was a blind weekend in there, and then I think it was three weeks later, the SMU game, and the fellow who had originally dated her in Fort Worth
I had invited her to come to the dance, come down for the weekend and do a dance there at the Lansing Museum.
Well, she came over to my door and said, you know, I don't think I'm going to have her dance.
I just don't feel like it.
I said, oh, don't do that.
She'd never been here before and it broke her heart.
I said, I'll help you out.
So I did.
Was it normal for the young man to pay for the railroad ticket?
Well, no.
Actually, they came on a bus.
It was a charter bus out of town.
It ran to all those kind of events.
And where did they stay in College Station?
Well, wherever they were.
Aggie could find a place for them.
Now the Aggie paid for that.
The Aggieland Inn was a hotel directly across west from Spesa.
And it could accommodate about how many?
I never knew, but I guess more than 15.
Where else near the campus?
Where else?
You just had to find a professor or...
Because there was no hotel or motel near the campus, was there?
No.
That's what I thought.
There was a couple of hotels in Brown, but they were a long way away.
I never had a date down there before.
Anyway, this boy had it all already lined up, so I helped him.
All right.
When, in today's terminology, when did you all start going steady?
Well, let's just say from that time on, we kept track of each other.
All right, and by the time you then leave for the active duty, you were serious?
Well, let's see, I guess I was.
You know, we had a war hanging over our heads all the time.
But you didn't get, did you get married before?
No, we...
I had already, in the summer of 43, I had a lead from 14.
And I went to Little Rock and told Glenn I already knew it.
And so we set up to get married when I got my commission.
And that was November the 18th, 1943.
The other night at home with some of the fellas, one of the fellas.
We were married in Little Rock.
Came down to Fort Worth to have a couple of days.
Michigan next evening and Texas next evening.
And then two of the other fellas that were my Aggie friends were also to be stationed at Camp Stewart, Georgia.
And so those two guys and Jane and I drove over there to the first station.
And then I immediately applied for
Air Force pilot training, and they weren't taking any commissioned officers.
And then Jane had heard of an engineering school at Yale, Aircraft Engineering School, and I applied for that, and it was accepted.
So we went to Yale on the 6th of February, 1944.
And, all right.
She stayed with me wherever I was in the States until I switched over to Japan.
And you go to Japan when?
I went to Japan in the fall of 1945.
Okay, so you get there, the war's over, all right.
Then you come back, let's now get back to College Station.
When do you return to finish your degree?
Well, I got, I was
My time in the Air Force, I transferred to the Air Force because my time in the Air Force was, you know, it was August of 12th, July of 12th, and I had some time to leave.
July and August of 45.
And I had
You may recall those four-plex project houses that were there on the southeast, southwest corner of Stamford.
We were extremely fortunate to get one of those.
And when was that?
August of 46.
All right.
Tell me how things were different in 46 compared to before the war.
Well, the campus was a big mixture.
Of course, the veterans were wearing whatever left over clothing they had.
I think they moved all of the Aggies, whatever all of D.C. there was at the time.
Well, I know they moved the freshmen.
Now, for you as a veteran, you didn't wear any Aggie uniform after the war.
Were the project houses pretty well filled with veterans?
Oh, they were exclusively for veterans.
They were first-class, brand-new accommodations.
Were there also some trailers and other temporary?
Not on the campus.
Not on the campus.
OK. And by and large, were the veterans at A&M, were most of them Aggies from before the war that were coming back to finish?
Oh, yeah.
OK.
Were there ever any incidents you remember between those of you who went away
And the 19-year-old nerd that had never had any part in the war, were there any incidents?
No.
Okay.
And was there a difference you'd felt in the attitude of the veteran about getting the degree compared to before the war?
Oh, yeah.
The degree or determination was just immeasurable.
I could cite to you a number of cases.
where a guy before the war had done just a full report.
He just didn't give a damn about class, and somehow they let him stay in.
He didn't care what the end was up or what.
And he came back, and don't know if he didn't whiz through getting a degree, and went on time, and went on to have a very fine business career.
The GI Bill is one of the greatest things that ever happened.
You betcha.
You betcha.
The guess is that the recipient of the GI Bill has paid back in extra income taxes that he wouldn't have earned 27 times as much as he receives.
So that's a win-win both ways.
I only got a...
I only got one semester of living there on the campus, and I never did collect any school tuition or airplane training or anything like that.
That's all I got.
It's not short.
While you and the other veterans were students, what were your wives doing in those years?
Well, Jan had a son that was... Jan was...
Okay, so she's busy being a mother.
Were there student wives working all over the campus?
Let's see.
Tell me about silver taps during your student days.
Was it held?
Where?

The givers would be up on top of the academic building, and it would be, they'd let them go, they'd let them go around, and they'd let it fall out, and outside they'd go on, and be there for the ceremony.
There was no, there was no enunciation,
since you your final semester or so you were not in the core you didn't go through a final review as a senior did you oh did you describe it where was it held but
What about Aggie Muster in those days?
Very informal.
Held where?
To tell you the truth, I don't remember one on the campus.
The first muster I became acquainted with was when I was working in Houston about 1950.
And it was basically a beer busted swimming club.
So that's gotten much more serious.
Oh, yeah.
It's gotten far more serious.
Were you there when some of the corrections
